      <h1 class="mb-8">Building Tools, Not Just Papers: Why I Code</h1>
      <div class="prose-page text-base leading-relaxed text-[var(--color-text)] space-y-4">
        <p>When I started this research, I had a choice: publish a paper pointing out that LLMs produce miscalibrated advice, or build a system that fixes it. I chose both.</p>
        <p>CheckMyCoach isn't just a paper contribution â€?it's 44 passing tests, a functioning API pipeline, a Streamlit frontend, and a cost per correction of ~$0.001.</p>
        <p>Why does this matter? Because <strong>trust calibration research needs to be deployable.</strong> If we find that AI advice is systematically misleading but only propose theoretical fixes, we've done half the job. The other half is building things that work.</p>
        <p>This philosophy extends to reproducibility. Every project on this site includes a quick-start guide, full environment specification, and tested code with CI.</p>
        <p>Not because it's required for publication, but because <strong>work you can't reproduce is work that doesn't exist.</strong></p>
      </div>
    </article>
